ce:section.ce:para:
To examine the fluorescence quenching (“turn-off”) mechanism, spectral characteristics of the as-fabricated B-CDs were studied. The emission peaks at 438, 516 and 543 nm are noticed for B-, G- and Y- CDs upon the excitation wavelengths of 325, 417 and 425 nm, respectively (Fig. 1
                        ). Additionally, the absorption peaks of three CDs were appeared at 318, 395 and 393 nm and the fabricated CDs exhibited different fluorescence colors when UV light exposed at 365 nm. The absorbance peaks were positioned at 318, 395 and 393 nm for B-, G- and Y- CDs, which are attributed to the π–π∗ and n-π∗ transitions. The excitation wavelengths of 325, 417 and 425 nm showed the maximum intensities at emission wavelengths of 438, 516 and 543 nm for B-, G- and Y- CDs, respectively (Fig. 1). The emission intensities of three fluorescent color CDs were recorded by exciting them at different wavelengths (Supporting Information of Fig. S1), revealing the emissions peaks of three CDs were gradually shifted from 439 to 494, 517 to 553 and 528–563 nm with decreasing intensities when excited at different wavelengths ranges from 300 to 420, 350 to 450 and 350–470 nm for B-, G- and Y-CDs (Supporting Information of Fig. S1). These results clearly demonstrated that the excitation dependent emissions were shown by three CDs. The quantum yields of fabricated CDs were estimated to be 18.0, 37.6 and 44.7% for B-, G- and Y- CDs using quinine sulphate and rhodamine 6G as references. Surface chemistry of three CDs was evaluated by FT-IR spectroscopy. As shown in Supporting Information of Fig. S2, the frequencies at 3109, 3413 (B- and Y- CDs), 2942, 2958, 2839 (B- G- and Y- CDs), 1645 and 1729 cm−1 are confirmed the stretching vibrations of –OH, -NH, -CH2, CC, C–N and CO groups of B-, G- and Y- CDs. Moreover, the frequencies at (524 cm−1), (880, 944 cm−1) and (1080, 1108 cm−1) correspond to P–O and PO groups stretching vibrations of G- and Y- CDs. These FT-IR spectral data demonstrated that the three CDs exhibited active surface functional groups, which could useful for the development of metal ion sensor. The HR-TEM images of nanosize B-, G- and Y- CDs are shown in Fig. 2
                        . The mean sizes of B-, G- and Y- CDs were estimated by measuring the histograms of HR-TEM images. The mean sizes of B-, G- and Y- CDs are 2.08 ± 0.48, 2.8 ± 0.62 and 4.0 ± 0.75 nm. Similarly, the hydrodynamic mean sizes of B-, G- and Y- CDs are 4.1 ± 0.9, 4.3 ± 0.6, and 13.7 ± 4.5 nm, revealing the as-synthesized CDs are very small sizes (Supporting Information of Fig. S3).

The effect of phosphate-buffered saline (PBS) pH was investigated on Fe3+ ion efficiency to quench fluorescence intensity at various pH ranges from 2.0 to 12.0 (Supporting Information of Fig. S5). These spectral data demonstrated that PBS pH did not show any remarkable changes on the quenching of fluorescence intensity of B-CDs. Thus, the calibration graph was constructed by measuring the emission intensity of nanosize B-CDs in the presence of various Fe3+ ion concentration (0.05–100 μM) without addition of PBS.To be more specific, the emission spectrum of nanosize B-CDs at 438 nm was quenched linearly with the addition of Fe3+ ion (0.05–500 μM) (Fig. 4
                        ), resulting a good linearity between the decreasing emission intensity at 438 nm versus the logarithmic plots of Fe3+ ion concentrations (0.05–100 μM). Noticeably, the fluorescence emission of nanosize B-CDs was quenched more than 50% by the addition of Fe3+ ion (500 μM), favouring a gradual decrease in the value of fluorescence intensity at 438 nm with increasing Fe3+ ion concentration. A calibration graph was constructed between the value of fluorescence peak at 438 nm and Fe3+ ion at different concentrations (0.05–100 μM) (Inset of Fig. 4). The regression equation was y = −15.327x + 173.4, R

                           2
                         = 0.9967 for Fe3+ ion and the limit of detection (LOD) was calculated as 0.03 μM for Fe3+ ion. Hence, the nanosize B-CDs act as an ideal probe for fluorescence assay of Fe3+ ion in real samples. Moreover, the analytical performance of the method was also evaluated by comparing the analytical parameters with the reported methods in terms of linear range and LOD (Tables 1 and 2

                        ) [45–56]. This comparison revealed that this method exhibited lower LOD value as compared to other nanomaterials-based analytical tools, signifying the practical application of the method for assaying of Fe3+ ion in real samples.
